French Blueberry Beignets

Yield: approximately 20 beignets

Dough

• 1 cup whole milk, warmed to 38–40 °C
• 2¼ tsp active dry yeast (1 packet)
• ¼ cup granulated sugar, divided
• 2 large eggs, room temperature
• ¼ cup unsalted butter, melted and fully cooled
• 1 tsp pure vanilla extract
• 3½ cups all-purpose flour
• ½ tsp fine sea salt
• 1 cup fresh blueberries, completely dry

⸻

For Frying

• Neutral oil (canola or grapeseed), for deep frying

⸻

Finishing

• Icing sugar, generously sifted
• Optional: finely grated lemon zest mixed into icing sugar

⸻

Method

Activate the yeast

Combine warm milk, yeast, and 1 tsp of the sugar. Rest 8–10 minutes until foamy and aromatic. If inactive, discard and restart.

⸻

Build the dough

In a large bowl, whisk eggs, remaining sugar, melted butter, and vanilla until smooth. Whisk in the yeast mixture.

In a separate bowl, combine flour and salt. Add to the wet ingredients and mix just until a soft, slightly tacky dough forms. Stop as soon as combined. The dough should be supple, not elastic.

⸻

Incorporate blueberries (critical control)

Spread blueberries on a tray and chill 10 minutes. Toss gently with 1 tsp flour.

Fold blueberries into the dough by hand, using a lift-and-turn motion. Stop immediately once evenly distributed. Berries must remain intact.

⸻

First rise

Cover and proof at 24–26 °C for 75–90 minutes, until doubled, airy, and fragile to the touch.

⸻

Shape

Turn dough onto a lightly floured surface. Pat gently to 1½ cm thickness. Cut into 5 cm squares or diamonds using a sharp knife or bench scraper. Do not twist or compress edges. Reroll scraps once only.

⸻

Second rest (non-negotiable)

Rest shaped beignets uncovered for 20 minutes. This lightly dries the surface, improves expansion, and reduces oil absorption.

⸻

Fry

Heat oil to 175 °C and maintain precisely.

Fry in small batches, turning once, until puffed and deep golden, 75–90 seconds per side. Adjust heat immediately if colour develops too quickly.

⸻

Drain and finish

Drain briefly on a rack (never paper towel). While hot, dust generously with icing sugar. Finish with lemon-zest sugar if using.

Serve immediately.

⸻

Target Texture

Light, hollow interior with tender crumb. Crisp exterior. No surface oiliness. Blueberries intact and juicy.

⸻

Chef-Level Technical Notes

• Blueberries must be dry and cold before folding.
• Minimal gluten development is essential for tenderness.
• Second uncovered rest is critical for clean fry behaviour.
• Oil below 170 °C causes grease absorption; above 180 °C scorches fruit sugars.
• Beignets do not hold. Fire to order only.
